definition.value: An oligonucleotide comprised of five thymidine residues connected via 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1-acyl group is specified as oleoyl.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as oleoyl and arachidonoyl respectively.
A polyketide isolated from fungi that is a potent inhibitor of fungal and mammalian squalene synthase.

A 17-oxo steroid that is androst-4-ene-3,17-dione in which the hydrogen at position 4 is replaced by a hydroxy group. Formestane was the first selective, type I steroidal aromatase inhibitor, suppressing oestrogen production from anabolic steroids or prohormones. It was formerly used in the treatment of oestrogen-receptor positive breast cancer in post-meopausal women. As it has poor oral bioavailability, it had to be administered by (fortnightly) intramuscular injection. It fell out of use with the subsequent development of cheaper, orally active aromatase inhibitors. Formestane is listed by the World Anti-Doping Agency as a substance prohibited from use by athletes.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol)(1-) in which the acyl group at position 1 is unspecified while that at position 2 is specified as oleoyl
An EC 2.5.1.* (non-methyl-alkyl or aryl transferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of squalene synthase (EC 2.5.1.21).
A 3',5'-cyclic pyrimidine nucleotide having uridine as the nucleobase.

A C-nitro compound that is 5-nitroimidazole in which the hydrogens at positions 1 and 2 are replaced by 3-chloro-2-hydroxypropyl and methyl groups, respectively. It is used in the treatment of susceptible protozoal infections and for the treatment of anaerobic bacterial infections.
A mixture obtained by combining equimolar amounts of hydrogen peroxide and urea.

A pyrimidine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside compound having 5-trifluoromethyluracil as the nucleobase. An antiviral drug used mainly in the treatment of primary keratoconjunctivitis and recurrent epithelial keratitis.

A cyclopentapyran that is (4aS,7aR)-1,4a,5,6,7,7a-hexahydrocyclopenta[c]pyran substituted at position 1 by an oxo group and at positions 4 and 7 by methyl groups, respectively (the 4aS,7S,7aR-diastereomer). An iridoid monoterpenoid isolated from several Nepeta plant species. It is an aphid sex pheromone and cat attractant, and exhibits antibacterial, antifungal, and analgesic properties.

A member of the class of sulfamides that is dichlofluanid in which the hydrogen at the para position of the phenyl group is replaced by a methyl group. A fungicide first marketed in 1971 and used in the cultivation of fruit and vegetables, as well as in wood preservatives, it is no longer approved for use in the European Union.
A 3',5'-cyclic pyrimidine nucleotide derived from thymidine monophosphate.
A diol that is pentane-1,5-diol in which the methylene group at position 3 is replaced by a sulfur atom
A mannosyl group derived from alpha-D-mannose.
A N-acyl-beta-D-galactosylsphingosine in which the acyl group is tetracosananoyl.
A mannosyl group derived from N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-alpha-D-mannose.
An alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosylceramide in which the substituent on the ceramide nitrogen is hexacosanoyl.
A mannosyl group derived from N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-alpha-D-mannose.

A cyclopentapyran that is (4aS,7aS)-1,4a,5,6,7,7a-hexahydrocyclopenta[c]pyran substituted at position 1 by an oxo group and at positions 4 and 7 by methyl groups, respectively (the 4aS,7S,7aS-diastereomer). An iridoid monoterpenoid isolated from several Nepeta plant species. It exhibits potent repellant activity against house dust mites and mosquitoes.
An EC 5.4.3.* (intramolecular transferase transferring amino groups) inhibitor that interferes with the action of lysine 2,3-aminomutase (EC 5.4.3.2).
An organic anionic group derived from N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-6-O-phosphonato-alpha-D-mannose(2-)
An acetate salt comprising equal numbers of acetate and thallium ions.
An organic chloride salt having tetrazolium violet(1+) as the counterion.
A 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol(1-) in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 36 carbons in total and 4 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol)(1-) in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 32 carbons in total with 0 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol)(1-) in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 32 carbons in total with 1 double bonds.
An organic cation that is the cationic component of tetrazolium violet.
An organic chloride salt having tetrazolium blue(1+) as the counterion.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol)(1-) in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 36 carbons in total with 1 double bond.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol)(1-) in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 36 carbons in total with 2 double bonds.
A 2-monolysocardiolipin(2-) in which the acyl group at position 2 is specified as dodecanoyl while those at positions 1 and 1' remain unspecified.
An organic cation that is the cationic component of tetrazolium blue.
A cardiolipin(2-) in which the 2'-acyl group is specified as lauroyl.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of (S)-3,5-dihydroxyphenylglycine.
A cardiolipin(2-) in which the 2'-acyl group is specified as linoleoyl.
A 2-monolysocardiolipin(2-) in which the acyl group at position 2 is specified as palmitoyl while those at positions 1 and 1' remain unspecified.
A 2-monolysocardiolipin(2-) in which the acyl group at position 2 is specified as stearoyl while those at positions 1 and 1' remain unspecified.
A 2-monolysocardiolipin(2-) in which the acyl group at position 2 is specified as linoleoyl while those at positions 1 and 1' remain unspecified.
Toxin isolated from marine segmented worm, Lumbriconereis heterodopa. It is also the active insecticide of the proinsecticide thiocyclam.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3,5-dihydroxyphenylglyoxylic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A gallotannin obtained by acylation of the five hydroxy groups of D-glucose by 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[(3,4,5-trihydroxybenzoyl)oxy]benzoic acid (a gallic acid dimer).

A dithiocarbamic ester that is 1,3,5-thiadiazinane with a thione moiety at position 2 and in which the hydrogens attached to the nitrogens are replaced by methyl groups. A fungicide, herbicide and nematicide, it is used prior to sowing or planting for the control of soil fungi, nematodes, bacteria and germinating weeds, and as fumigant for poultry litter and eggs to control Salmonella. It is a non-ozone-depleting alternative to methyl bromide.
A hydrate that is the dihydrate form of sodium molybdate.
A 1-(alk-1-enyl)-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the 2-acyl substituent is specified as acetyl.
An inorganic sodium salt having molybdate as the counterion.
A 1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl group is specified as octadecyl
A glycosylceramide in which the glycosyl moiety is alpha-D-galactose and the ceramide is N-(hexacosanoyl)-11,12-methylene-C22-sphinganine.
